Now, the net present value is solved as follows: 



&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{NPV}&=\$3,154,697.28-\$1,800,000\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,354,697.28}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the net present value of the project is $1,354,697.28 if the first year of the project is a success.

Then, the net present value is solved as follows: 



&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{NPV}&=\$1,139,196.24-\$1,800,000\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{(\$660,803.76)}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the net present value of the project is ($660,803.76) if the first year of the project is a failure scenario. 

The NPV resulted into a negative amount, therefore, the company might consider abandoning this project if sales are at 3,900 units.

Using the equation in Step 12, the value of the option to abandon the project is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Value to Abandon}&=\frac{\$1,139,196.24}{\left(1+0.14\right)^{10}}\\[20pt]
&=\frac{\$1,139,196.24}{\left(1.14\right)^{10}}\\[20pt]
&=\frac{\$1,139,196.24}{3.7072}\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{\$307,292.90}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the value of the option to abandon the project is $307,292.90.
